default&#xa0;
defaultCase examples
default - 
defaultThe case of Mr
default A
defaultThis year we were forced to issue a case in the High Court because a local authority had failed to provide adequate care to an individual suffering from Muscular Dystrophy. This person had been left with no choice b
defaultut to live on a sofa for five years without any care being offered by the authority in question. The clients’ father, aged 80 had to meet his   son’s care needs, whilst also providing care for his wife, aged 79 whom suffered from Alzheimer’s disease. Moreo
defaultver, the local authority had been obstructing the Claimant’s access to a Disabled Facilities Grant to enable him required adaptations to extend his parent’s house for the purpose of building an additional bedroom.
defaultWe attempted negotiations for eight months
default and sent numerous letters before action. We applied for judicial review but the local authority had made some concessions the day before a permission hearing. We had a full day
default oral
default permission hearing but we were not granted permission but instead given a
default second permission hearing despite the first hearing resulting in a positive order for our client. The local authority failed to comply with the order and for the second time the
default oral permission
default hearing lasted a whole day. The hearing again resulted in a p
defaultositive order. However, we were not granted permission due to last minute concessions finally made on the authority’s part following the second order. We were instead given a third permission hearing. Currently, a Disabled Facilities Grant has been agreed 
defaultand a care package offered, yet we were never granted permission by the High Court. This is a common occurrence and the reason why the statistics in community care cases do not provide an accurate picture.  
defaultThis case would be classified as not having permi
defaultssion.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe case of Mr B
defaultIn this matter the local authority were about to remove a person with severe autism from his care home as they thought it was
default too
default expensive. They had not found an adequate place to meet his needs and had not even carried out a ne
defaultw needs assessment, care plan or risk assessment of what the effect could be. We were instructed two weeks before the proposed move which his parents had been protesting against. With the threat of judicial review placed upon the local authority the local 
defaultauthority have decided to take no action and stated in correspondence that this was only because of the threat of judicial review. 
default We have had to keep this case open as the local authority appear to be waiting until we go away so they can remove him. 
default&#xa0;
defaultTh
defaulte case of Mr C
defaultThis client was threatened with being evicted from his care home despite serious safeguarding issues. He was given 7 days notice and told that he should report to the local authority homeless section stating he was homeless. There was no nee
defaultds assessment 
defaultor care provision put in place. His father contacted us and we contacted the local authority
default. The local authority back
defaulted
default down immediately with the threat of judicial review. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe case of Miss D
defaultThe client was not receiving an amount of care to meet her needs, the local authority would not state how the needs were met or increase the care package. She has Multiple 
defaultSclerosis
default and required a high degree of care. We threatened judicial review which ha
defaultd no effect so we issued a claim in the high court and they back down immediately agreeing 
defaultto provide
default reasons and to reassess her care package. She was then given an increased care package. 
defaultThis case would be classified as not having permission. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe 
defaultcase
default of Mr E
defaultThis case involved a mother whom looked after her severely disabled son whom had a multitude of disabilities. 
defaultIn this matter the loca
defaultl authority would not provide a 
defaultcarers assessment, we sent numerous letters before claim and had meetings. We fina
defaultlly issued in the high court and they gave in within one hour of receiving notification from us of having issued the case. In this matter they contacted the LAA and tried to have the certificate taken away. 
defaultThis case would be classified as not having permi
defaultssion.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe case of Miss F
defaultThis case involved a mother with a severe disability who required a Disabled Facilities Grant but the local aut
defaulthority would not allow her to apply. They stated they were not allowed to under the law. We instructed a barrister, po
defaultinted out that they had discretion and that there was guidance within the guidance and again threatened Judicial Review. And again they back down 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe case of Miss G
defaultIn this matter a 
defaultperson with so severe care needs that they required 24 hour care was giv
defaulten an assessment and then reduced to only a few hours a week. Again we threatened Judicial Review and they put the 24 hour care back in place. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe complaints procedure
defaultIt has been often argued that those with disabilities can use the complaints procedure
default. We can state that from our experience and our clients experience that the complaints procedure is not fit for purpose. The local authorities have a vested interest in stating that there has been no wrongdoing on their part. 
defaultOften issues can be matter of 
defaultlife or death 
default(i.e. someone’s 24 care package being reduced to 4 one hour visits per day).
default&#xa0;
default Therefore 
defaulta 
defaultcomplaint is clearly not a viable option,
defaultIncreasingly we are hearing reports from callers to our advice line that their complaints are not being dealt with, or are being dismissed out of hand with little or no fair and transparent consideration of the facts by the local authority.
default&#xa0;
default This is sympto
defaultmatic of a complaints procedure being controlled by the organisation being complained about.
default&#xa0;
default This used to be the case with complaints against the police until it was acknowledged that you need a degree of independence when dealing with issues.
default&#xa0;
default At a time 
defaultwhen local authorities are having their budgets put under increasing pressure, and are having to make financially sensitive decisions, it is vital that an independent body is responsible for dealing with complaints.
default&#xa0;
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultConclusion
defaultWe have many of these 
defaultexamples and our advice lines show the same material and why there is a need for the Judicial Review or a tribunal with the same powers including the ability to make an urgent and immediate decision which is legally enforceable.
